# Feature Descriptors

1. SIFT (Scale-Invariant Feature Transform)

    Good online material, check [here](https://aishack.in/tutorials/sift-scale-invariant-feature-transform-introduction/) or simply Wikipedia.
   1. Construct Scale Space

        1. For same scale, different gaussian kernels are applied on the image to create scale space, e.g. $[\sigma_i, 2\sigma_i]$  and descretized to $2^{\frac{i}{s-1}}\sigma_i$, $s$ is the number of images in one octave (same scale level)
        2. Down sample the image with scale of multiple of 2 to create new octaves.
   2. Take Difference of Gaussians

        1. Approximate the Laplace of Gaussian with Difference of Gaussians.
        2. Compute differences between two consective images in the same octave, thus, in total $s-1$ DoGs.
   3. Locate DoG Extrema

        Comparing each pixel in the DoG images to its 8 neighbors at the same scale and 9 corresponding neighboring pixels in each of the neighboring scales. If the pixel value is the maximum or minimum among all compared pixels, it is selected as a candidate keypoint. Therefore, in total, it requires at most 26 comparisons to decide whether it is the candidate keypoint. Check figure below. 
        ![Locate DoG Extrema][extrema]
   4. Sub-pixel Locate Potential Feature Points
   5. Filter Edge and Low Contrast Responses
   6. Assign Keypoints Orientations
   7. Buid Keypoint Descriptors
   8. Further Steps
